Module kivakit.core
Package com.telenav.kivakit.core.path

Class Path<Element extends Comparable<Element>>

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.kivakit.core.path.Path<Element>
All Implemented Interfaces:
com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.collection.Emptiness, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.collection.Sized, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.AsString, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.StringFormattable, Comparable<Path<Element>>, Iterable<Element>
Direct Known Subclasses:
StringPath
public abstract class Path<Element extends Comparable<Element>> extends Object implements Iterable<Element>, Comparable<Path<Element>>, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.collection.Sized, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.StringFormattable
Abstraction of an immutable path of elements of a given type with an optional root element. Functional methods in Path work on subtypes of Path because subtypes implement copy() to return the correct subtype.

Kinds of Paths

  • "" - The empty path (with no elements and no root)
  • "/" - The root path (UNIX)
  • "C:\" - A root path (Windows)
  • "D:\" - A root path (Windows)
  • "/a/b/c" - Absolute path
  • "a/b/c" - Relative path

Relative and Absolute Paths

Paths that have a root() element are absolute and isAbsolute() will return true. Any path without a root is a relative path and isRelative() will return true. A root path has a root element but no path elements and isRoot() will return true. The empty path has neither a root nor any elements and isEmpty() will return true.

Adding Elements

  • push(Comparable)

Element Retrieval

  • elements() - The elements in this path
  • first() - The first element in the path or null if there is none
  • first(int) - The first n elements in the path or null if there are fewer elements
  • get(int) - The nth element in the path or null if there is no nth element
  • iterator() - The elements in this path
  • last() - The last element in the path or null if there is none
  • last(int) - The last n elements in the path or null if there are fewer elements
  • pop()
  • rootElement() - The root element, if any
  • stream() - A stream of the elements in this path (not including the root)

Parenting

  • parent()
  • root()
  • rootElement()

Conversion

  • asString(Format)

Comparison

  • compareTo(Path)
  • endsWith(Path) - True if this path ends with the given path
  • startsWith(Path) - True if this path starts with the given path

Checks

  • isAbsolute() - True if this path has a root element
  • isEmpty() - True if this path has no root and no elements
  • isRelative() - True if this path does not have a root element
  • isRoot() - True if this path has a root element but no path elements

Functional Methods

The following methods are functional, meaning that they return a copy of the path that is changed in some way while this path itself is not altered. The copy is made with the method copy(), which calls the subclass to create the copy through onCopy(Comparable, List). This allows subclasses to reuse the logic in this class while still dealing in instances of the subclass type.

  • copy() - A copy of this path
  • emptyPath() - The empty path
  • parent() - The parent of this path
  • root() - The root path of this path
  • subpath(int start, int end) - The elements from start to end (exclusive)
  • transformed(Function) - This path with each element transformed by the given function
  • withChild(Element) - This path with the given element appended
  • withChild(Path) - This path with the given path appended
  • withParent(Element) - This path with the given element prepended
  • withParent(Path) - This path with the given element prepended
  • withRoot(Element) - This path with the given root element
  • withoutFirst() - This path without any first element or null if there is no first element
  • withoutLast() - This path without any last element or null if there is no last element
  • withoutOptionalPrefix(Path) - This path without the prefix, if it exists
  • withoutOptionalSuffix(Path) - This path without the suffix, if it exists
  • withoutPrefix(Path) - This path without the given prefix path or null if it is not found
  • withoutRoot() - This path without the root element
  • withoutSuffix(Path) - This path without the given suffix path or null if it is not found

    • subpath

      public Path<Element> subpath(int start, int end)
      Returns the sub-path of this path starting at given start index (inclusive) and extending to the end index (exclusive). If start and end are equal, the empty path is returned. If start and end are not equal and the path is absolute, the sub-path will still be absolute with the same root. If the start and end indexes are invalid, null is returned.

    • withoutFirst

      public Path<Element> withoutFirst()
      Returns this path without the first element. If this is an empty path, null is returned. If there is only one element in this path, the root path or empty path is returned, for absolute and relative paths, respectively.

    • withoutLast

      public Path<Element> withoutLast()
      Returns this path without the last element. If this is an empty path, null is returned. If there is only one element in this path, the root path is returned. If there is only one element in this path, the root path or empty path is returned, for absolute and relative paths, respectively.

    • withoutOptionalPrefix

      public Path<Element> withoutOptionalPrefix(Path<Element> prefix)
      Returns this path without the given prefix. If this path doesn't start with the prefix, the path is returned unchanged.

    • withoutOptionalSuffix

      public Path<Element> withoutOptionalSuffix(Path<Element> suffix)
      Returns this path without the given suffix. If this path doesn't end with the suffix, the path is returned unchanged.

    • withoutPrefix

      public Path<Element> withoutPrefix(Path<Element> prefix)
      Returns this path after the given prefix. If the path doesn't start with the prefix null is returned. If the path is equal to the prefix, a root or empty path is returned for absolute and relative paths respectively.

    • withoutRoot

      public Path<Element> withoutRoot()
      Returns this path without the root element or null if this path is a root element

    • withoutSuffix

      public Path<Element> withoutSuffix(Path<Element> suffix)
      Returns this path before the given suffix. If the path doesn't end with the suffix null is returned. If the path doesn't start with the prefix null is returned. If the path * is equal to the prefix, a root or empty path is returned for absolute and relative paths respectively.
